s_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do games represent history, and how do we make sense of the history of games? The industry regularly uses history to sell products, while processes of creation and of promotion leave behind markers of a game’s history. The access to this history is often granted by so-called paratexts, which are accompanying elements orbiting texts. Exploring this fully, case studies in this work move the focus of debate from the games themselves to wider, ancillary materials and ask how history is used in, and how we can use history to study games.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistory in video games. 0aVideo gamesxHistoryxCase studies. 4aDigitale Kultur. 4aParatext. 4aRezeption. 4aVideospiel. 7aGAMES & ACTIVITIES / Video & Electronic.2bisacsh  adigital culture.  aparatext.  areception.  avideo games.1 aDonald, Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForget, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaley, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacCallum-Stewart, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPennington, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Andrew James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeiwald, Regina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSeiwald, Regina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStevens, E. Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVollans, Ed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 